body: Sorry, we stopped supporting CentOS6. You may try to build onnxruntime from source with red hat devtoolset. Instructions are at: https://www.onnxruntime.ai/docs/how-to/build.html
What CentOS version does onnxruntime support?
I hit the exactly same issue on ubuntu 18.04. We stopped supporting CentOS6 since 1.7, but @yaoyuannnn can only see ORT 1.4.
I can install 1.7 successfully under conda environment with the same python version (3.6).

> I can install 1.7 successfully under conda environment with the same python version (3.6).

Thanks for reopening this! Did you install it on CentOS 6? What was the command you used?
I tried on ubuntu 18.04, not on CentOS 6. You can try installing conda and then pip install install onnxruntime in conda env.

> I tried on ubuntu 18.04, not on CentOS 6. You can try installing conda and then pip install install onnxruntime in conda env.

I was actually using conda. I was only able to see ORT 1.4 as the newest version though.

You can find all the tech details at https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0599/. 

For example, "The wheel may only contain binary executables and shared objects compiled for one of the following architectures supported by CentOS 7, or a CentOS 7 compatible base image ". It means, CentOS 7 is the minimum requirement.  Ubuntu 16 and 18 are supported too because their glibc versions are newer. 

onnxruntime python package conforms to manylinux2014, which requires pip >= 19.3. If you are using CentOS 7 rh-python38, CentOS 8 python38, Fedora 32+, Mageia 8+, Photon OS 4.0+ (3.0+ with updates) or Ubuntu 20.04+, then by default the pip program is new enough. Otherwise, please update it before installing onnxruntime.
I removed the release:1.7 tag because it is not a 1.7 release issue.
